title: For Sale:  Rare Romanian Contract 1934 Beretta Pistol W/2 WWII Mags
postcontent:
Rare Romanian Contract 1934 Beretta Pistol W/2 WWII Mags. Here is a Romanian contract 1934 Beretta military pistol assembled in 1941, as indicated by the markings on the left side of the slide, and with two original Beretta magazines. The back of the right side of the frame displays Romanian armory mark, "CM". No import markings. 
CONDITION: Excellent, with 97-98% of original blue still on the metal. All matching serial numbers (frame, slide, barrel). Fine bore with strong and shiny rifling. Very smooth action. Difficult to find pistol without the import marks! Caliber: 9 mm Short (.380 ACP, marked on barrel). Two WWII Beretta magazines with thin metal floorplates and no other markings, both in like new condition (as is the pistol!).

This Beretta model 1934 pistol offered here was manufactured for the Romanian military in 1941. In August of 1940, the Romanian military placed a contract with Beretta for 61,000 model 1934 pistols. This contract specified that the pistols were to be delivered within seven months. The first of these pistols was not delivered until February of 1941 due to the shortage of steel and Romania's failure to send Beretta the entire fund amount for the pistols. Beginning in February of 1941, Beretta delivered 10,000 pistols with the promise of 5,000 more per month until the total contract was filled. By August of 1941, Beretta had sent a total of 40,000 pistols, but the remaining 21,000 were never delivered. This means that there are less then 40,000 of these pistols in existence today. The first of these Romanian contract pistols can be identified with a 0(zero) at the beginning of the 5 digit serial number. The Romanian contract pistols are identical to the Italian model 1934 versions except that the slide is marked 9 SCURT instead of 9mm Corto as seen in the pictures below. These Romanian model 1934 pistols were normally issued to the Romanian officers 
during WW2.
$950.00

Very rare! Lightly used Smith and Wesson Model 19-2 in very good condition. Has cylinder and holster wear. This Smith and Wesson revolver is one of the original production 'Combat Magnum' Model 19's and is the '-4 variants produced from 1961 to early 1999 It contains all original parts and has matching serial numbers on the frame, grip, 

This Smith and Wesson Model 19-2 is chambered in .357 magnum with a 4 pinned barrel and 6 round capacity. This firearm has the original old-style rear sight leaf screw placement. This gun contains all original parts/grips 

The Model 19 was Smith and Wesson's first .357 magnum mass produced handgun, and the '-4 variant was the second variant ever produced. The Model 19 was produced in blued carbon steel or nickel-plated steel with wood or rubber combat grips, an adjustable rear sight, semi-target hammer, serrated combat-type trigger, and was available in 2.5", 4", or 6-inch barrel lengths. The Model 19 was produced from 1957 to November 1999.

title: For Sale/Trade:  W German Sig P226 w 5 mags, real SEAL holster, case, $750
postcontent:
I have a much sought after West German marked Sig P226 9mm. This is one of the ones that has the slide, frame and barrel all marked with the same serial number. This is one of the Sigs that were made back when Sigs were actually Sigs. This one was made with the rare original (and also sought after) grips. 

If you know anything about Sigs then you likely know that the above three-serial number West German marked ones is the tip of the spear. This is also the EXACT configuration that the US Navy SEALs originally adopted (before the MK25) and from what I hear back from the Sand Box, many are still using this version as they prefer it over the MK25 (the one with the rail and the cute little anchor on it). 

I also have FIVE original Sig 15rd magazines. 4 of them are the authentic Sig-made, German "zipper-back" mags and one of them is a Metgar that was made for Sig and is marked with Sigs logo. They all run flawlessly. 

Here's the coolest part. I'm also including an AUTHENTIC US Navy SEAL Safariland "drop leg" holster that has been "operator-modified" by the SEAL who owned it. The modifications are the ones that almost ALL SEALs and DELTA guys do on these Safariland holsters: They shorten the belt strap so that the gun rides higher (on the hip) rather than way down flopping around on their leg. They also cut off the top strap so they can sinch the bottom strap high up into the groin to keep everything nice and streamlined. Next they drill a hole through the holster and attach a bungie that can be slipped around the gun's handle when parachuting so as to keep the gun more secure and add a second retention device as they free fall. Lastly they paint the previously black holster (it's like a hard, rough plastic) FDE (which is like a tan color). 

This holster is the real deal and I personally know the operator who wore this in combat operations in "the Sand Box". You'll have to just trust me because no, I'm not giving you his name but he's a tier-1 operator and this holster has seen some serious operations. The holster still has the USN ID painted on it (in red). 

Lastly, I'm including the original Law Enforcement Only box that this weapon came in. These boxes themselves are actually quite rare and people on the Sig forums buy these. 

This was a duty holster so there are wear marks on the front of the slide from coming into and out of the holster and there are the minor dings and scratches that you'd expect to see from an actual duty holster. If you're looking for beauty queen; keep looking. If you're looking for a bad ass man gun then this is it. 

Between the weapon itself (a Florida SWAT deputy's duty weapon) and the AUTHENTIC Navy SEAL holster, there is a lot of history on this package. 

All five of the magazines are currently loaded with Speer Gold Dot duty rounds. I'll let you keep all the rounds too.

I am looking to get an AR10 or an AR15, so would like to trade, or sell this gun. Asking for $675 cash. Will listen to any reasonable offer/trade. Also included 300 rds or ammo. You can email me or text me @ REDACTED.

Must have valid Purchase Permit or CCW. Below is the retailers statement about the gun:

Introduced in January 2010, the Centurion 39 is a new semi-automatic version of the AK-47 design, and it retains all the signature AK features, such as the curved 30-round magazine, 7.62x39 mm chambering, and an oversize, right-side safety lever. Unlike other AKs sold in this country, which are usually assembled using foreign-made parts kits, the Centurion is made completely in the United States.
The Centurion 39 conveys an impression of extreme sturdiness, with robust and simple internal components, and a receiver machined from an 11-pound block of 4140 steel. Century Arms states that the rifle is also made to tighter tolerances than the original.
The Centurion, however, incorporates a number of changes to the original design. For example, its 16 1/2-inch barrel terminates in Century’s proprietary three-port Chevron Compensator. Created expressly for the Centurion, this removable unit more effectively directs propellant gas upward to reduce muzzle jump.
Also departing from the original pattern are the Centurion’s sights. On standard AK variants, windage adjustments are performed by moving the front sight. On the Centurion, the square-notch rear sight has been redesigned to allow windage changes by loosening a set screw and moving the rear sight blade laterally. Elevation is adjusted by a slider on the rear tangent sight or by rotating the red-colored front sight post.
The Centurion’s most visually distinguishing features are its polymer buttstock and two-piece polymer handguard. The buttstock has a 1-inch longer length of pull than the original wood stock—better fitting American shooters—and terminates in a ribbed, plastic buttpad. The handguard features four Picatinny rail segments spaced 90 degrees apart for the mounting of optics, lights and other accessories. Molded-in checkered panels on the lower handguard aid grip, while numerous ventilation slots in the upper handguard help cool the enclosed gas tube assembly.
Two TAPCO 30-round polymer magazines come with each rifle. Century Int’l states that the Centurion accepts standard AK accessories, including the company’s own MTL-225 Tactical Fore-end Weapon Light, which combines a 225-lumen light with a vertical fore-grip and mounts on the rifle’s bottom Picatinny rail. Disassembly follows standard AK-47 procedures, as is thoroughly explained in the rifle’s owner’s manual.

The entire firearm could easily be summed up in a single phrase; "Grimy, but undamaged". There's no physical damage on the rifle, but there are plenty of signs of long storage. Dusty barrel, worn laminate, bits of dried mud inside the checker-pattern on the buttstock, etc

Since the picture, the rifle has been touched up considerably; everything but the barrel has been rubbed down and cleaned, all metal parts have been oiled.

I am reluctant to sell this rifle; I have yet to fire it and it was my uncle's prized possession. Alas, I have no more room in my gun safes, and my house is far too humid to allow firearms of any sort to sit in the open for long.

I'm not looking to gouge anyone with the price here; I'm a collector as well and I know how infuriating it is when dealers jack up the price just because. I searched Armslist to find similar condition Winchesters and based the price off of that, taking off $100 for the 'damage' the rifle has. This is a golden opportunity for anyone who wants a .30-30, and is willing to spend a few hours cleaning it up instead of buying new for hundreds more.


Please, feel free to email me at anytime. From there I can give you my cell phone number, and we can schedule a time to come take a peek at the rifle. This is a first-come, first-served basis. Cash only, and the price is firm.

It would be easiest to meet me at my house, where all the guns are anyways, but I am willing to meet anywhere in the Portland area. Please bear in mind I have a very odd weekend from work 'Wed-Thur'.

Happy Hunting,
      Thomas
